statement.p:
The average (mean) of a set of n numbers y_1, y_2, \cdots, y_n is


y_\ave =\bar y = \llt y\rgt =\frac{y_1+y_2+\cdots+y_n}{n}


The notations y_\ave, \bar y and \llt y\rgt are all commonly used to represent the average.

introduction.p:
gives us a link between the average value and the area under the curve. The right-hand  side is the area of the region


\big\{(x,y)\ \big|\ a\le x\le b,\ 0\le y\le f(x)\ \big\}


while the left-hand side can be seen as the area of a rectangle of width b-a  and height f_\ave. Since these areas must be the same, we interpret f_\ave as  the height of the rectangle which has the same width and the same area as  \big\{(x,y)\ \big|\ a\le x\le b,\ 0\le y\le f(x)\ \big\}.

example.p:
Solution: We can just plug things into the definition.


  f_\ave &= \frac{1}{5-1}\int_1^5 x \dee{x}

  &= \frac{1}{4} \bigg[ \frac{x^2}{2} \bigg]_1^5

  &= \frac{1}{8} (25-1) = \frac{24}{8}

  &= 3


as we might expect. And then


g_\ave &= \frac{1}{5-1}\int_1^5 x^2 \dee{x}

  &= \frac{1}{4} \bigg[ \frac{x^3}{3} \bigg]_1^5

  &= \frac{1}{12} (125-1) = \frac{124}{12}

&= \frac{31}{3}

Solution: Again, we just need the definition.


  \text{average} &= \frac{1}{\frac{\pi}{2} - 0} \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \sin(x) \dee{x}

&= \frac{2}{\pi} \cdot \bigg[ -\cos(x) \bigg]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}}

&= \frac{2}{\pi} (-\cos(\frac{\pi}{2})+\cos(0))

&= \frac{2}{\pi}.

Let x(t) be the position at time t of a car moving along the x-axis. The velocity of the car at time t is the derivative v(t)=x'(t). The average velocity of the car over the time interval a\le t\le b is


v_\ave &= \frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b v(t)\dee{t}

&=\frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b x'(t)\dee{t}

&=\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a} & \text{by the fundamental theorem of calculus.}


The numerator in this formula is just the displacement (net distance travelled  if  x'(t)\ge 0, it's the distance travelled) between time a and time b and the  denominator is just the time it took.

Since the voltage is a sine-function, it takes both positive and negative values. If we  take its simple average over 1 period then we get


  V_\ave &= \frac{1}{2\pi-0} \int_0^{2\pi} V_0 \sin(t) \dee{t}

  &= \frac{V_0}{2\pi}\bigg[ - \cos(t)\bigg]_0^{2\pi}

  &= \frac{V_0}{2\pi}\left( -\cos(2\pi) + \cos 0\right) = \frac{V_0}{2\pi}(-1+1)

  &= 0


This is clearly not a good indication of the typical voltage.

What we actually want here is a measure of how far the voltage is from zero. Now we could  do this by taking the average of |V(t)|, but this is a little harder to work with.  Instead we take the average of the square

		For a finite  set of numbers one can compute the quadratic mean which is another way to generalise  the notion of the average:

		\text{quadratic mean}
		= \sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\left(y_1^2 + y_2^2 + \cdots + y_n^2 \right) }


of the voltage (so it is always positive) and then take the square root at the end. That is


  V_\mathrm{rms}
  &= \sqrt{\frac{1}{2\pi-0} \int_0^{2\pi} V(t)^2 \dee{t}}

  &= \sqrt{\frac{1}{2\pi} \int_0^{2\pi} V_0^2 \sin^2(t) \dee{t}}

  &= \sqrt{\frac{V_0^2}{2\pi} \int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2(t) \dee{t}}


This is called the root mean square voltage.

Though we do know how to integrate sine and cosine, we don't (yet) know how to integrate their squares. A quick look at double-angle formulas

		A quick glance at  Appendix will refresh your memory.

gives us a way to eliminate the  square:


  \cos(2\theta) =1-2\sin^2\theta \implies \sin^2\theta=\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}


Using this we manipulate our integrand a little more:


V_\mathrm{rms} &= \sqrt{\frac{V_0^2}{2\pi} \int_0^{2\pi}  \frac{1}{2}(1-\cos(2t)) \dee{t}}

&= \sqrt{ \frac{V_0^2}{4\pi} \bigg[t - \frac{1}{2}\sin(2t)  \bigg]_0^{2\pi} }

&= \sqrt{ \frac{V_0^2}{4\pi} \left(2\pi - \frac{1}{2}\sin(4\pi) - 0 + \frac{1}{2}\sin(0) \right) }

&= \sqrt{ \frac{V_0^2}{4\pi} \cdot 2\pi }

&= \frac{V_0}{\sqrt{2}}


So if the peak voltage is 170 volts then the RMS voltage is \frac{170}{\sqrt{2}}\approx  120.2.

Again we simplify the integrand using the identity

\cos(2\theta) =1-2\sin^2\theta \implies \sin^2\theta=\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}

So


P_\ave &= \frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b P(t)\dee{t}
  = \frac{V_0^2}{2R(b-a)}\int_a^b \big[1-\cos(2\omega t-2\delta)\big]\dee{t}

&=\frac{V_0^2}{2R(b-a)}\bigg[t-\frac{\sin(2\omega t-2\delta)}{2\omega}\bigg]_a^b

&=\frac{V_0^2}{2R(b-a)}\bigg[b-a-\frac{\sin(2\omega b-2\delta)}{2\omega}
  +\frac{\sin(2\omega a-2\delta)}{2\omega}\bigg]

&=\frac{V_0^2}{2R}
   -\frac{V_0^2}{4\omega R(b-a)}\big[\sin(2\omega b-2\delta)-\sin(2\omega a-2\delta)\big]


In the limit as the length of the time interval b-a tends to infinity, this converges to \frac{V_0^2}{2R}. The resistance R of a 100 watt bulb  obeys


\frac{V_0^2}{2R} &=100 & \text{so that} && R &= \frac{V_0^2}{200}.


We finish this example off with two side remarks.



	If we translate the peak voltage to the root mean square voltage using


	  V_0 &= V_\mathrm{rms} \cdot \sqrt{2}


	then we have


	  P &= \frac{V^2_{\mathrm{rms}}}{R}





	If we were using direct voltage rather than alternating current then the  computation is  much simpler. The voltage and current are constants, so


	  P &= V \cdot I & \text{but $I = V/R$ by Ohm's law}

	  &= \frac{V^2}{R}


	So if we have a direct current giving voltage equal to the root mean square voltage, then  we would expend the same power.
